Knowledge of the earth's magnetic field seems to have affected measurability in a negative manner. The magnetic fields on Uranus and Neptune were at odds with our understanding of magnetic fields. 

<quote>
"The more remarkable is that the Earth's magnetic field is dipolar from where we stand on the surface and approximately axially symmetric. That's why we expect that on other planets," said Lilley.
</quote>

leading to <a href="http://www.science-frontiers.com/sf070/sf070a04.htm">such comments</a> as 

<quote>
he axis of the earth's magnetic field is tilted about 11ï¿½ away from our planet's axis of rotation. This tilt is embarrassing to the reigning "dynamo theory," in which the axes of the magnetic field and rotation are presumed to be aligned. The situation is even worse with some the other planets; viz., Uranus with 60ï¿½ and Neptune with 47ï¿½. Jupiter's tilt is 10ï¿½, while Saturn's is only 1ï¿½. Clearly, something is awry.
