Kyler Kuehn argues

<quote>
Habitability alone may be compelling (in, e.g., cosmological fine-tuning arguments), but the Privileged Planet Hypothesis requires a non-trivial correlation of both!
<ref><a href="http://www.ps.uci.edu/~kuehn/personal/ID2004.ppt">A critique of the Privileged Planet Hypothesis</a> by Kyler Kuehn presented at the <i>Intelligent Design and the Future of Science</i> conference . Biola University. April 22-24, 2004</ref></quote>



Convinced of Purpose in our universe, these arguments may appear to be convincing but such should not be confused with a scientific foundation for said 'Purpose' or even an ability of science to address the nature of this 'Purpose'. Since the Privileged Planet thesis does not identify how to measure a weighted optimality, fails to address the causal links between correlations and fails to provide more than a single datapoint (remember that their argument is a weighted one so the earth cannot be more than a single data point), I conclude that we have to reject, once again, the Privileged Planet leap of faith.


<quote>
All of this is consistent with the argument we develop in The Privileged Planet. We do not argue that habitable environments like Earth are superior to less habitable environments for every type of scientific measurement and discovery. Such an argument would be obviously incorrect. (Recall the superiority of intergalactic space for measuring the background radiation.) Rather, we argue that habitable environments provide the best overall setting for a wide range of diverse and often competing set of prerequisites for such discovery
</quote>

No wonder Kyler Kuehn concludes 

<quote>
Inclusion of the Privileged Planet Hypothesis in educational curricula is not (yet) warranted.
</quote>

